# Security Layer: Kubernetes and Infrastructure Governance

## Workload Identity Mandate

- All pod-to-GCP authentication MUST use Workload Identity Federation.
- No service account keys, no secret JSON files, no environment variable credentials.
- Each agent role (RH, LH, Operator) gets its own KSA-to-GSA binding with minimal IAM roles.

## Pod Security

- All LH (executor) pods MUST run with `runtimeClassName: gvisor` for kernel-level isolation.
- All containers MUST set `allowPrivilegeEscalation: false` and `readOnlyRootFilesystem: true`.
- The `employee` namespace MUST enforce the `restricted` PodSecurityStandard.

## Network Isolation

- LH pods may only reach Vertex AI endpoints and the operator service.
- No lateral pod-to-pod communication in the `employee` namespace.
- NetworkPolicies MUST be applied before any workload is deployed.

## Resource Governance

- ResourceQuotas on the `employee` namespace prevent sub-agent sprawl.
- The operator MUST enforce pod count limits when spawning LH executors.
- All Terraform resources must use the smallest viable tier for the current environment.

## Secret Management

- No secrets in Kubernetes manifests, Dockerfiles, or Terraform files.
- All sensitive values come from Workload Identity or GCP Secret Manager.
- `.gitignore` must exclude all credential files, `.env`, and `*.tfvars`.
